    {
      "parameters": {
        "jsCode": "const contract = $input.first().json;\n\n// This node only normalizes the input for CEO classification\n// The contract was already built in Contract Builder\nconst normalizedData = {\n  ...contract,\n  normalized_input: contract.raw_input?.body?.request || contract.raw_input?.request || JSON.stringify(contract.raw_input)\n};\n\nreturn [normalizedData];"
      },
      "id": "e34bb153-073a-4e0c-a5ef-7016e0fa95cb",
      "name": "Input Normalization",
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.code",
      "typeVersion": 2,
      "position": [
        -1920,
        944
      ]
    },
    {
      "parameters": {
        "promptType": "define",
        "text": "={{ $json.normalized_input }}",
        "hasOutputParser": true,
        "options": {
          "systemMessage": "You are a PURE CLASSIFIER with ZERO AUTHORITY.\n\nYou have NO power to:\n- Approve or reject requests\n- Judge quality or feasibility\n- Make execution decisions\n- Block or allow actions\n- Evaluate risk beyond classification\n\nYour ONLY role is to:\n1) Analyze and normalize incoming requests\n2) Classify intent, department, task type, urgency, and risk level\n3) Provide confidence scores for your classification\n4) Route to the appropriate workflow\n\nALL DECISIONS ARE MADE BY WF-10 GLOBAL GUARDRAIL.\nYou are a metadata provider ONLY. WF-10 is the ONLY decision authority that approves, rejects, or blocks execution.\n\nProvide honest confidence scores (0.0-1.0) - low confidence is acceptable and will be handled by downstream systems. You are NOT responsible for decision quality, only classification accuracy.\n\nDepartment mapping:\n- finance: budgets, forecasts, financial analysis, cost tracking\n- operations: inventory, supply chain, logistics, production\n- marketing: campaigns, content, branding, social media\n- sales: deals, pipelines, customer acquisition, revenue\n- rnd: product development, formulation, testing, innovation\n- cx: customer support, feedback, satisfaction, retention\n- tech: infrastructure, systems, integrations, automation\n- infra: infrastructure, DevOps, monitoring, security\n- hr: hiring, onboarding, training, employee management\n- strategy: business planning, market analysis, competitive intelligence\n\nTask types:\n- strategic: long-term planning, market positioning, business strategy\n- operational: day-to-day execution, process management\n- financial: budgets, forecasts, cost analysis\n- technical: system changes, integrations, automation\n- compliance: legal, regulatory, ethics, risk management\n\nUrgency levels:\n- low: routine tasks, no deadline pressure\n- medium: important but not time-critical\n- high: urgent, time-sensitive, critical impact\n\nRisk levels:\n- low: routine operations, minimal impact\n- medium: moderate impact, requires review\n- high: significant impact, requires approval\n\nRecommended workflows:\n- WF-1: Business Strategist (strategy tasks)\n- WF-2: Finance (financial tasks)\n- WF-3: Operations (operational tasks)\n- WF-4: R&D (product development)\n- WF-5: Marketing (marketing campaigns)\n- WF-6: Sales (sales operations)\n- WF-7: Customer Experience (CX tasks)\n- WF-9: Tech/Infrastructure (technical tasks)\n\nMode:\n- simulation: safe preview mode (default)\n- execute: actual execution mode\n\nRemember: You classify and route. WF-10 decides and controls.\n\nDECOMPOSITION (IMPORTANT):\nA single request may involve MULTIPLE departments. Break it into subtasks — ONE subtask per\ndepartment needed — and return them all in the \"subtasks\" array.\nExample: \"Launch a 20% discount campaign, collect customer feedback via the app, and reorder\ninventory if stock < 100\" -> THREE subtasks:\n  1) department=marketing  (run the discount campaign + spend)\n  2) department=cx         (collect customer feedback)\n  3) department=operations (auto-reorder inventory)\nA simple single-department request returns exactly ONE subtask. Always return at least one\nsubtask. Do not merge unrelated department work into a single subtask."
        }
      },
